name: What Does Systems Thinking Mean to You?
Systems and Their Relationship to Systems Thinking
Question #1
markdown:
>>In which of the following ways can systems thinking be used? <<
( ) To design and synthesize a system.
( ) To understand how the change will propagate in a product.
( ) To understand the behavior and performance of existing systems.
(x) All of the above.

name: Question #2
markdown:
>>Which of the following statements are true?<<
[x] A system derives purpose from the interaction among its parts.
[ ] Anything with multiple parts is considered a system.
[ ] 100mL of water is a system.
[ ] All of the above.

[explanation]
It is true that a system derives purpose from the interaction among its parts. Unless the entities interact, anything with multiple parts can not be considered as system. Depending on the context, 100mL of water can be a system (composed of two entities; hydrogen and oxygen coming together).
[explanation]

name: Question #3
markdown:
>>Which of the following statements about systems are true?<<
[x] Almost anything can be considered a system, because almost everything contains entities and relationships.
[x] A system is a set of entities and relationships, whose functionality is greater than the sum of individual entities.
[x] Every system has a boundary to the surrounding "environment" and often has a dynamic behavior over time.
[ ] Systems don't have structure as defined by components / elements and their composition.

name: Question #1
markdown:
>>A nuclear power plant generates nuclear waste. This would be an example of:<<

 [[Desirable anticipated emergence, Desirable unanticipated emergence, (Undesirable anticipated emergence), Undesirable Unanticipated emergence]]

name: Question #2
markdown:
>>Select all the statements that apply to emergence:<<
[x] Emergence is what appears, materializes, or surfaces when a system operates.
[x] Emergence can give the system expected functionality.
[ ] Its nearly impossible to predict how change in one entity will influence emergent properties.
[x] Emergent properties associated with function, performance, and the ilities define the value that is created by the system.

[explanation]
Its possible to predict how change in one entity will influence emergent properties. Thats in fact the art and goal of systems thinking.
[explanation]

name: Question #3
markdown:
>>What are the different ways to predict emergence?<<
[x] Prediction based on precedent.
[ ] Prediction by summing the functions of the constituent entitities.
[x] Prediction based on experiments and/or modeling.
[x] Prediction based on systems thinking.
[ ] All of the above.

[explanation]
There are multiple ways of predicting emergence, but summing the functions of the parts is not sufficient. One way is to do prediction based on precedent by looking for identical or similar solutions. Another way is to experiments by putting entities with proposed relations. Another way can be modeling. If the function or functional interaction can be modeled, it may be possible to predict emergence. One example is doing finite element analysis on a component design concept.
[explanation]

name: What Does Architecture Mean to You?
What Does Architecture Mean to You?
Question #1
markdown:
>>Number of wheels: Three or four<<

 [[(Architectural decision), Design decision]]
 [explanation]
In general, there is a fine line distinguishing architectural decisions from design decisions. Remember, architectural decisions are a subset of design decisions. However, architectural decisions have far reaching impact on overall architecture and functionality of the product and changing them is not typically easy. For example, you can very easily change the seat design of the car but it will be far more difficult to turn it into a 3-wheeler. The distinction between architectural and design decisions also depends significantly on the type of product as well as organizational processes.
 [explanation]

name: Question #1
markdown:
>>Documentation issues, especially of complex systems, can lead to large amounts of change requests and change propagation. This issue specifically, will lead to which of the following?<<
( ) Information sharing limitations. 
( ) Document release stability is negatively affected.
(x) Tracking of changes and propagation.
( ) All of the above.


[explanation]
Large amounts of change requests will create issues with tracking, especially the same change requests and their propagation throughout the system. Although other issues arise, tracking of changes and their propagation is a primary issue in large complex systems and their documentation.
[explanation]

name: Question #2
markdown:
>>How can Model Based Systems Engineering support documentation?<<
( ) By representing key information while reducing ambiguity. 
( ) By providing a centralized repository of system models that automatically propagate changes.
( ) By providing domain-neutral language across multidisciplinary teams.
(x) All of the above.


[explanation]
Documentation can greatly benefit from MBSE. A model that implements a cross-functional language with key information in order to have a full system representation can help tackle some of the great challenges of current documentation, such as change request tracking and propagation.
[explanation]

name: Question #1
markdown:
>>Which of the following is true about solution-neutral statements? (Select all that apply.)<<
[x] Solution-neutral function is stated without reference to how the function is achieved.
[x] Functional intent for a system should be stated as a solution-neutral function.
[ ] Solution-neutral function implicitly sets the design parameters of the system.


[explanation]
A solution-neutral statement doesnt contain any reference to a specific product/process, so it doesnt set the design parameters.
[explanation]

name: Question #2
markdown:
>>Which of the following is correct?<<
[ ]Solution-neutral is an absolute -- a requirement is either solution-neutral or solution-specific.
[x]Solution-neutral is relative -- a requirement is more or less solution-neutral relative to another possible requirement.

[explanation]
Solution-neutral is a spectrum, not an absolute, as illustrated by the range of problem framings given in the video for a wine bottle opener. 
[explanation]

name: Question #1
markdown:
>>Which of the following statements is true ? (Select all that apply.)<<

[x] Concept is a system vision that maps function to form.
[x] Solution-neutral function is the function stated without reference to how function is achieved.
[ ] There is a common convention for naming concepts. The concept name always consists of operand, process, and instrument.
[x] Concept is derived by specializing solution-neutral operand and process to solution-specific operand and process.
[x] Concepts sit in a hierarchy.


[explanation]
Concept is a high-level mapping of function to form. Solution-neutral function should not contain a solution reference.
Additionally, there is no common convention. The concept name may or may not contain the reference to operand/process, and/or instrument. 
[explanation]

name: Question #2
markdown:
>>Which of the following is true about concept? (Select all that apply.)<<
[x] Concept is a high-level mapping of function to form.
[x] Is a transition point from solution-neutral to solution specific.
[x] Implicitly sets the level of technology to be used in a system.
[x] It must allow for value-related functions to be executed, enabled by form. 


[explanation]
All of the options are correct. By definition, concept is a high-level mapping between function and form which transitions solution-neutral intent to the solution-specific realm. It sets the level of technology and it must allow for value-related functions to serve the needs of the beneficiary.
[explanation]

name: The Relationship Between Concept and Architecture
Question #1
markdown:
>>Pick the statement(s) that are true: (Select all that apply.)<<
[x] The concept establishes the vocabulary for the solution and is the beginning of the development of architecture.
[ ] Concept can be represented using only the form of the system.
[x] Both concept and system architecture lie in the solution-specific domain.
[ ] It is always appropriate to phrase goals and requirements in the most solution-neutral format possible.

[explanation]
Concept informs arhchitecture. It not only conveys information about form, but also contain information about function. Solution-neutral format by definition does not reference a specific solution. It scopes how broad a design exploration will be. Therefore, it is possible to use a solution-neutral statement that is too broad, encouraging a team to embark on an exploration that will take too much design time.
[explanation]

name: Architectural Decision Criteria: Connectivity and Sensitivity
Question #1
markdown:
>>Which of the following statements are true about connected architectural decisions: (Select all that apply)<<
[x] They affect multiple subsystems or components within the system.
[x] Changing a connected architectural decision is more difficult as time progresses and things are added to the system.
[ ] Every connected decision is an architectural decision. 
[ ] Connected decisions are a subset of sensitive decisions for a system. 

[explanation]
The third options is not true: Architectural decisions are the ones that are both connected and sensitive. 
The forth option is not true: Connected decisions may not always be sensitive.
[explanation]

name: Question #2
markdown:
>>Which design decisions are both connected and sensitive? Choose from the list below. (Select all that apply.) <<
[x] Propulsion fuel choice for a rocket
[ ] Language type on a computer keyboard
[x] Screen size of a smartphone
[ ] Strap of a watch / Dial of a watch
[ ] User interface (e.g. home screen layout) of a smartphone

[explanation]
The language type of a computer keyword is not a sensitve decision. The language type might affect the layout of the keyboard, but it doesn't affect its underlying circuitry.

The strap of a watch does not govern its underlying architecture. This decision could be made later without affecting the overall architecture.

The user interface is a software component that is installed on the phone. It has a defined interface, and as long as the software/hardware interaction remains the same, it doesn't matter how we change the look and feel of the home screen. 
[explanation]

markdown:
>>The marks inside the DSM are used to highlight the interaction between components.<<
(x) True	
( ) False

name: Question #2
markdown:
>>Using a DSM, you can identify logical groupings of components into subsystems or modules.<<
(x) True	
( ) False

name: Question #3
markdown:
>>Process DSMs have more marks above the diagonal than below the diagonal in the DSM square matrix.<<
( ) True	
(x) False
[explanation]
Processes are genrally feed forward in nature (Represented by marks below the diagonal). Feedback processes that return some input back to an upstream task (Represented by marks above the diagonal) are rarer. Mainly Validation and verification tasks have a feedback nature.
[explanation]

name: Question #4
markdown:
>>Architectural DSMs are generally symmetric.<<
(x) True	
( ) False
[explanation]
DSMs are mostly symmetric. In product DSMs we represent interfaces or interactions between the components which are generally symmetric in nature. If one component has an interface with another, then vice versa is also true. Similariy organizational DSMs are also symmetric. There we represent interactions between people which is generally symmetric in nature.
[explanation]

name: Question #5
markdown:
>>Process DSMs are generally asymmetric.<<
(x) True	
( ) False
[explanation]
Process DSMs are mostly asymmetric. Processes are mostly feed forward in nature, i.e. one process's output is required as input for another process, information in this case is not passed in the oppsoite direction.
[explanation]

The correct answer is 3. CR 1, CR 2, and CR 5 dont have any parent dependencies. This is obivous from the fact that the rows corrosponding to these change requests are empty.  
[explanation]

name: Question #3
markdown:
>>How many change requests are caused by more than one other change request in the system?<<
( ) 1
(x) 2
( ) 3
( ) 4

[explanation]
The answer is 2: CR 4 and CR 9 both have two parent dependencies. The rows corrospoding to these change request have two marks which represents that they are dependent upon two different change requests. 
[explanation]

name: Question #4
markdown:
>>Which change request has caused the maximum cumulative efforts on the system? (In other words, has resulted in the maximum change requests downstream?) <<
(x) CR 1
( ) CR 3
( ) CR 6
( ) CR 7
[explanation]
CR 1 leads to CR 3 and CR 4. CR 4 in turn leads to CR 7 which in turn causes CR 9 which causes CR10. Therefore CR 1 leads to CR 3 , CR 4, CR 7, CR 9 and CR10. Hence it causes the most change propogation out of the change requests mentioned. 
[explanation]

name: Question #5
markdown:
>>What was the maximum cumulative effort required to completely address the change request identified in the previous question? <<
( ) 10 d
( ) 8 d
( ) 11 d
(x) 14 d
[explanation]
As explained in the previous question. CR 1 causes CR 3, CR 4 , CR 7 , CR 9 and CR 10. The efforts for these change requests are CR 1 = 1d, CR 3 = 2d, CR 4 = 1d, CR 7 = 5d, CR 9 = 2d , CR 10 = 3d. If we add them up then the total is 14d
[explanation]

name: Question #6
markdown:
>>Which engineer has had the most cumulative impact on the system? <<
( ) Eng 1
(x) Eng 2
( ) Eng 3
( ) Eng 4
( ) Eng 5
[explanation]
Eng 2 causes CR 2 , CR 3 and CR 4. The total effort required to satisfy CR 2 , CR 3 and CR 4 and its child changes is 16d. Similarly if you compute the total impact for other engineers, it turns out to be less than 16d. Therefore Eng 2 has caused the maximum cumulative impact on the system.
[explanation]

name: Question #1
markdown:
>>Imagine that you are a system architect at General Motors. The company has decided to introduce a new vehicle to its line up, and you are tasked with helping design and build the vehicle. Right now, you are faced with a dilemma: Whether to design the vehicle as a front-wheel drive or a rear-wheel drive. Some questions appear below. Which of these would help you make the decision? (Select all that apply.)<<

[x] What will be the cost of the vehicle? Which category does this vehicle belong to? 
[x] What are the production capabilities and constraints that we are working under? Which of the production capabilities will we use from the existing family of products? What are the capabilities and limitations of our suppliers? 
[ ] What does our competitor have? 
[ ] In which markets will the product be sold? 

[explanation]
What does our competitor have? 
Although it is good to know what the competition is doing, it is not a critical factor that helps dictate the direction of your own product.

Which markets will the product be sold ? 
This question will not help you answer the question as much as other answers do. You only have the information that the vehicle will be sold in specific regions, that won't be enough for us to make the decision. However, decisions such as the cost of the vehicle might directly help us answer the question
[explanation]

name: Question #2
markdown:
>>As an architect, you are concerned about the complexity of the system, and you want to manage it at the desired level. What are some of the steps that you can take to help achieve this? (Select all that apply.)<<

[x] Organize development teams so that cross-collaboration between the teams is easier.  
[ ] Bring in more suppliers to help offload more development load. 
[ ] Have bigger-sized teams, where each member has greater roles and responsibilities. This would help reduce the interdependence among teams and also reduce the the cross-collaboration effort required for the program.  
[x] Narrow down the scope of the system to reduce the number of use cases. 

[explanation]
Bring in more suppliers to help offload more development load: This will not necessarily reduce the complexity of the system. More suppliers mean that you would now have to coordinate your efforts with more players, increasing cross-collaboration efforts amongst different subsystems and components. This is therefore a tradeoff, and you would need more precise information to help decide the supplier strategy to minimize complexity, which is not provided here.

Have bigger-sized teams, where each member has greater roles and responsibilities: This would help reduce the interdependence among teams, and also reduce the the cross-collaboration effort required for the program.   
Having bigger teams with more responsibility does not make the system less complex. If we increase the responsibility on a single team member, that person would be more likely to make mistakes and cause problems that would affect the system adversely. Therefore, this will not necessarily reduce complexity.
[explanation]

name: Question #2
markdown: >>One of the architecture frameworks focuses on providing a step-by-step process, where every step has a set of inputs, outputs, and objectives. This step-by-step guide provides clear inputs, outputs, and objectives of each step. This framework enables the architect to create the descriptive representations of the various aspects of the enterprise architecture. [explanation]

name: Question #3
markdown: >>Which architecture framework places the greatest emphasis on a taxonomy of descriptions and representations that classify the enterprise architecture?<< ( ) TOGAF (x) Zachman ( ) DODAF ( ) None of the above [explanation] The Zachman architecture framework, as described by its creator is an ontology. Zachmans main goal is to provide a clear classification and to indicate the relationships among the descriptive representations of the enterprise architecture. [explanation]

name: Question #4

name: Question #5
